  "prompt": "What is the legal history of money laundering prohibitions?",
  "response": "The legal history of money laundering prohibitions can be traced through several key developments:\n\n1. Early Origins:\n- Informal anti-money laundering (AML) practices emerged in the 1920s during Prohibition in the United States\n- Criminal organizations sought ways to make illicit gains appear legitimate\n\n2. Bank Secrecy Act (1970):\n- First comprehensive U.S. legislation targeting financial crimes\n- Required financial institutions to report large cash transactions\n- Introduced record-keeping requirements for banks\n\n3. International Developments:\n- 1980s: Growing international recognition of money laundering as a global problem\n- Emergence of international cooperation to combat financial crimes\n\n4. Critical Milestone - Basel Committee (1988):\n- Established initial international guidelines for preventing money laundering\n- Recommended banks implement customer identification and transaction monitoring\n\n5. United Nations Convention (1988):\n- Criminalized money laundering related to drug trafficking\n- Encouraged international collaboration in investigating financial crimes\n\n6. USA PATRIOT Act (2001):\n- Significantly expanded AML regulations post-9/11\n- Enhanced reporting requirements\n- Increased penalties for non-compliance\n\n7. Modern Global Framework:\n- Financial Action Task Force (FATF) became primary international standard-setting body\n- Developed comprehensive recommendations for national legal systems\n\nThis progression reflects increasing global sophistication in combating financial crimes.",
